It sure would be neat if NASA could invent some better space suits! They seem so complex and bulky  and if they could thin them down a bit while still being durable and airtight  it might make repairs way easier to do  plus then the astronauts could wear them inside  if they were comfortable enough  and be safe if there was a sudden depressurization!  Plus if NASA could invent really cool  affordable  space proof armor  similar technology might be used for sea diving or hazardous activities or even cool normal wear in a durable suit made from some kind of neat  yet cheap (optional?) material  like those new graphite materials they keep inventing.  I also think it would be cool if NASA put some of its efforts into cost-cutting  so that spaceship fuel and parts and maintence and assembly were all way cheaper  so that private industry space flights  putting satellites into orbit  even tourists and more luxurious space stations and living on other planets  could all become possible and profitable with a massive decrease in the price and complexity of space travel!  I for one would love to see spaceships be as common as jets  with companies scrambling to build them as fast as possible and put satellites into orbit and do other capitalistic deeds in order to maximize profits  invent cool new stuff  explore the solar system  mine the other planets  start colonies  and more  all hinged on cheap space flight (and some biodomes  too).

I was wondering about that nuclear powered spaceship  which I think was 'cassini'? And someone mentioned it only had 70lbs of nuclear pellet fuel....so I understand the risk of explosion  but is there some reason it didn't have say  7 tons of nuclear fuel instead of 70lbs? Is the fuel very expensive? Also how big of a hazard would an explosion be?  I was thinking one reason to colonize other planets would be to reduce the risk of nuclear explosion/radiation  and that the moon might be a great place to build a nuclear launch facility  since the moon is already irradiated by the sun and a lack of an atmosphere  plus the escape velocity of the moon is much lower than the earth.  I also think it should be possible to obtain nuclear materials on the moon itself  without having to ship them there from earth  because of my theory that because uranium and plutonium are minerals  they are formed under the surface of the moon (and all other planets) by the crushing force of gravity and all the materials on top of them - thus  if you drill or dig deep enough  you should be able to find uranium and plutonium to fuel rockets deep in the moon  without any environmental concerns since the biodomes will already have to be shielded against radiation.

Do you want to see history in the making? Check out this video. This one event has the potential to change Human civilization forever. Instead of just throwing the booster into the ocean  we bring it back. We refurbish it  and we reuse it. Humans do it  and in spectacular fashion too. You've got to admit  this is cool as all get out.  When you look at those people cheering at the historic first landing recovery of a booster  try to keep in mind. Those people work in California and Florida and other places hands on to build all that stuff. They get paid good money to do it. That's where Bernie Sanders education program comes in.   Our nation needs educated hands to build the 21st Century lifestyle we want. We Humans want to expand our presence to the cosmos. This type of endeavour enables that. So let's pour money into expanding into the cosmos. To building colonies on Mars and the moon. To mining resources both material and of energy. To exploit and harvest the bounty of the universe  and thus preserve the Earth.  Please remember  the $16 trillion the American people used to bail out Wall Street and "to big to fail" banks was enough to have funded 91 Apollo programs from start to finish. From Mercury to the last two canceled Apollo missions  $16 trillion could of done all of that times 91. If our nation had of made a commitment in 2008 to build solar arrays in orbit around the Earth  beaming solar energy to collectors on the ground  I'm pretty sure $16 trillion could of done the job. Even asteroid mining for platinum and rare earth metals could of been had. All we needed to do is put our minds to it  and the money. Just call me stupid  but I have a feeling that 91 Apollo size programs might have been enough to get asteroid mining going.  Let us not forget all the jobs created too! Look at them people cheering. Now think of the Apollo program. At its peak the Apollo program employed 400 000 people and the services of 20 000 businesses and universities. What I'm saying is  if we had of put the $16 trillion into 91 Apollo size projects  perhaps we could of put 91 X 400 000 = 36 400 000 people to work. We could of been asking China to take some of our excess jobs instead of struggling to get back the jobs we lost.  Honestly  we all got screwed big time with all that bailout mess. Instead of building the future of our civilization  we gave it all away to greedy crooks.  You know that national effort to build an atomic bomb? We need the same urgency and sense of purpose in rekindling the American spirit of exploration and expansion. Obama wants to rekindle the spirit of innovation. Well  here is the way to do it.  Put $16 trillion into the creation of a national effort and commitment for a program 91 times the size of Apollo to expand Humanity's presence into our planetary neighborhood. That would include colonies on the moon and Mars  orbital habitat around Earth the moon and Mars  orbital solar power collection grids  asteroid mining operations and processing facilities  Earth based infrastructure and support systems  training and education programs  and retrofitting existing factories and facilities for use with this national effort.  Think big!
